# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

## Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | App crashes at runtime |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never thrown** | Dead code, rollback never fires |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | App crashes at runtime |
| Manual `Thread` + `volatile bool` | Works, but inferior to modern APIs | Missed cancellation while blocked |

The `volatile bool` pattern has a subtle bug: if `GetNextItem()` **blocks** (as the comment suggests), setting `_running = false` won't unblock it — `Stop()` hangs or must resort to the now-removed `Abort()`.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<WorkItem> _channel;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public BackgroundProcessor(int capacity = 128)
    {
        _channel = Channel.CreateBounded<WorkItem>(new BoundedChannelOptions(capacity)
        {
            FullMode = BoundedChannelFullMode.Wait
        });
    }

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    public void Enqueue(WorkItem item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Queue is full or completed.");
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            // ReadAllAsync yields items and unblocks on cancellation
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                try
                {
                    ProcessItem(item);
                }
                catch (Exception ex) when (ex is not OperationCanceledException)
                {
                    // Replace ThreadAbortException handler —
                    // cancellation now arrives via the token, not thread abort
                    RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                }
                finally
                {
                    FlushBuffers();
                }
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Graceful shutdown requested — not an error
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);

        // 1. Signal no more items will be written
        _channel.Writer.TryComplete();

        // 2. Give the loop time to drain naturally
        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            var finished = await Task.WhenAny(
                _workerTask,
                Task.Delay(timeout.Value));

            // 3. If still running, cancel via token (replaces Thread.Abort)
            if (finished != _workerTask)
            {
                await _cts.CancelAsync();  // .NET 8 — thread-safe cancel
                try { await _workerTask; }
                catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void ProcessItem(WorkItem item) { /* ... */ }
    private void RollbackCurrentTransaction() { /* ... */ }
    private void FlushBuffers() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Migration Decisions

**1. `CancellationToken` replaces `Thread.Abort()`**
The token cooperatively unblocks `ReadAllAsync`, `Task.Delay`, and any other async API — no blocked-thread problem.

**2. `Channel<T>` replaces blocking `GetNextItem()`**
Channels provide backpressure, async reads that respect cancellation, and are lock-free on the fast path.

**3. Two-phase shutdown replaces `Sleep` + `Abort`**
Complete the channel → drain remaining items → cancel if stuck. Deterministic, no arbitrary `Sleep(2000)`.

**4. `catch (Exception) when (...)` replaces `catch (ThreadAbortException)`**
Since `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown in .NET 8, map your rollback logic to the failure paths that actually occur.

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Compiles but crashes** | `Thread.Abort()` compiles (API exists) but throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime |
| **`CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` in `finally`** | Can deadlock if called on the worker thread — use `CancelAsync()` (.NET 8+) from the caller |
| **Forgetting to pass the token** | If `ProcessItem` does I/O, pass `ct` through so it can be interrupted too |
| **`Task.Run` without storing the Task** | Fire-and-forget swallows exceptions silently — always store and await |
| **Disposing `CTS` too early** | Dispose only after the worker task has fully completed |
